{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"A\n    \n      \"Mission Control Academy\"\n      Structure: Each page is a mission briefing. Short intro text sets the scene, then a sequence of standalone interactive widgets teach each concept. Scroll down = next experiment.\n      Interactives: Self-contained simulations per concept. Circuit builder, battery cell cross-section, grid balancing game, storage tech comparison tool. Each widget is a \"station\" you can play with independently.\n      Vibe: Science museum meets spy HQ. Each widget feels like a classified experiment you're running. Glowing borders, data readouts, status indicators.\n      Effort: ~15-20 interactive components across 4 pages. Each is modular and independent.\n      Pros: Modular (can build/ship incrementally), each interactive is reusable, easy to maintain\n      Cons: Less narrative cohesion between widgets, potentially feels like a textbook with fancy illustrations","choice":"a","id":null,"timestamp":1774182999518}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"B\n    \n      \"Explorable Explanations\"\n      Structure: Each page is one continuous scroll-driven experience. As you scroll, the visualization transforms and responds. Text and interactive are fused — you can't separate them.\n      Interactives: The entire page IS the interactive. Scroll position drives animation state. Sticky canvas elements that morph as you read. Inline sliders/toggles that modify the ongoing visualization in real-time.\n      Vibe: Like a Bartosz Ciechanowski deep-dive or an NYT visual essay, but in mission-control dark mode. Immersive and cinematic.\n      Effort: ~4 large scroll-driven experiences. Each is a single complex component managing many states.\n      Pros: Most immersive and memorable, strongest narrative flow, truly unique\n      Cons: Highest complexity per page, harder to maintain, scroll-driven state machines are tricky, mobile experience needs extra work","choice":"b","id":null,"timestamp":1774183003825}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"C\n    \n      \"Hybrid: Briefings + Labs\"\n      Structure: Each page has 2 layers. A \"briefing\" layer (prose + embedded scroll-driven animations for key concepts) and \"lab\" sections (standalone interactive playgrounds you can explore freely). Best of both worlds.\n      Interactives: 2-3 scroll-driven explorable sections per page for the core narrative, plus 1-2 standalone \"lab\" simulations at the end or inline for deeper exploration.\n      Vibe: Read the briefing, then run the experiment. The briefing builds intuition, the lab lets you test it.\n      Effort: ~8-10 scroll-driven sections + ~8-10 standalone labs across 4 pages. Medium-high complexity.\n      Pros: Narrative cohesion from scroll-driven parts, replayability from standalone labs, can ship briefings first and add labs iteratively\n      Cons: Two interaction paradigms on one page could feel inconsistent if not designed carefully","choice":"c","id":null,"timestamp":1774183004613}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"A\n    \n      \"Mission Control Academy\"\n      Structure: Each page is a mission briefing. Short intro text sets the scene, then a sequence of standalone interactive widgets teach each concept. Scroll down = next experiment.\n      Interactives: Self-contained simulations per concept. Circuit builder, battery cell cross-section, grid balancing game, storage tech comparison tool. Each widget is a \"station\" you can play with independently.\n      Vibe: Science museum meets spy HQ. Each widget feels like a classified experiment you're running. Glowing borders, data readouts, status indicators.\n      Effort: ~15-20 interactive components across 4 pages. Each is modular and independent.\n      Pros: Modular (can build/ship incrementally), each interactive is reusable, easy to maintain\n      Cons: Less narrative cohesion between widgets, potentially feels like a textbook with fancy illustrations","choice":"a","id":null,"timestamp":1774183006613}
